text: This looks so good- and so real as we will see this more and more. I love the book The Inspired Caregiver - Finding Joy While Caring for Those You Love...it's  for caregivers who are caring for their parents and loved ones with dementia and Azheimer's - for the health of the caregiver. Alzheimers' patients will eventually live in their own world- but caregivers have to experience two deaths! We have to mourn the death of HOW our loved one used to be- and then the actually death.    When Julianne talks about living in the moment, that is all we can all do... for tomorrow isn't promised. We have to find a cure for this disease- it's increasing at an alarming speed. Someday we will need a caregiver, be a caregiver, or both.

text: You can have expectations of your children, and let them know what you want for them, your children don't have to listen to that, or follow your wishes and any feeling of it being an unfair pressure can be taken in one of many ways. One way, would be to understand that the mother has a terminal disease, and wants her daughter to know what she wants for her why she can still express it, whether her daughter feels ready or not for that information or advice doesn't bear any relevance in this example, because the mother is saying it whilst she still can. The timing is no longer able to be chosen. Any way. It is a line in a film.... But it is also an honest reflection of a very human situation, and of course a great topic for discussion. In my humble opinion the line delivered, in the film, and indeed if it were delivered in real time in a similar situation, is not at all bad, because it is loaded and delivered with love and good intention, positivity and encouragement to progress in life.

text: We read this book in my neuropsychology class. We were told to not read the description or look it up. Our professor wanted us to find out what was happening and what the story was about as we went. It's crazy how much more a book can affect you, especially emotionally, when you don't know what to expect, and you don't know what is going to happen or how to prepare for it. The worst part is once you find out, you want to help, you would do anything just to give them back their memories and happiness but you can't and neither can any doctor or medication in the world. It's an amazing book and I'm sure the movie will be just as great! It pulls on the heart strings, but it really opens up your eyes to how lucky we are for everyday things like our memory, family, and  friends. Go tell your family you love them while you can! God bless!
author: Emily K

text: This trailer made me cry, it's a slice of my life. I'm only 17 and my dad has dementia and he's only 54. I thought I would have time before I had my last conversation with him but it's too late now bc he doesn't comprehend anything. At first when I heard of Alzheimer's and dementia, I thought I would never experience anything like this, the odds are so small so it really doesn't matter what happens to them. But then it happened to my family and now, there's no help. It really sucks: 1)how there's no cure and 2)how naive and ignorant I was to all the victims of Alzheimer's and dementia.  I'm sorry to the victims because you're not the only ones who get affected...but your family does too.

Kristen's usual roles are apathetic, awkward AND realistic, just like Jesse Eisenberg. Does he get the same amount of hate that Kristen gets? I bet not. I am so sorry, but I'm just so sick of people bullying her. You all need to quit and focus on your own lives. Her roles are always so moving and touching, people need to see that behind this whole 'Kristen Stewart as Bella Swan' thing. All people do to her is bully her, you all need to stop. text: I was about six or seven when my Pa got alzheimer's. I don't remember much about it, my parents stopped taking my sisters and I to see him as often as we used to because they didn't want our last memories of him to be his asking who we were. I still remember though that his favourite thing was to tell us stories, whether they were made up or true. He remembered my oldest sister for the longest before he passed but I think him eventually forgetting her really broke her heart because they were always so close...
